    dfischer.utils.HttpLoadTest.httpResponseOk(HttpTestURL, int, int, int, String, String)
    since version 5.2-O. Compare during a load test the received response with the originally recorded values (content string test) - allow additionally an alternate HTTP status code. If the comparison fails, an error will recorded inside the binary result file and a short error text will be inserted inside the log vector.
     
    Additional of searching the occurrence of a simple string, the following special search patterns are supported:
    • ![<search text>] means that the search text must not occur inside the received content.
    • #<int>[<search text>] means that the search text occurs exactly <int> times inside the received content.
    • #<int>-[<search text>] means that the search text occurs at minimum <int> times inside the received content.
    • #<int1>-<int2>[<search text>] means that the search text occurs at minimum <int1> times but not more than <int2> times inside the received content.
     
    Search String Examples:
    helloThe search text "hello" must occur at least one time inside the received content
    ![ORA-01652]The search text "ORA-01652" must not occur inside the received content
    #1[Dear Mr.]The search text "Dear Mr." must occur exactly one time inside the received content
    #1-2[Order Number]The search text "Order Number" must occur at minimum one time and at maximum two times inside the received content
    #3-[new order]The search text "new order" must occur at minimum three times inside the received content
    dfischer.utils.HttpLoadTest.httpResponseOk(HttpTestURL, int, int, int, String, String, String, String)
    since version 5.2-O.     dfischer.utils.DNSTranslationTable(File)
    since V5.4-K, does not support encrypted DNS translation file. Create a new instance which is initialized with the content of a DNS translation file. The DNS translation file is a text file that contains on each line a translation between two DNS names. If the first DNS name in the file match to the DNS name that is passed to the resolver then the second DNS name is used to resolve the IP address. The first DNS name can also contain one or more wildcard characters ('*' = wildcard for multiple characters, '?' = wildcard for single character). Lines or a part of a line can be commented out by using the hash char '#'.

    DNS translation file example: 

     www.proxy*sniffer.com  www.d-fischer.com # comment
 #comment
 www.mutong.com www.d-fischer.com
 mail?.google.com       mail.google.com
    Note 1: It could be needed that TLS SNI (Server Name Indication) must be disabled if a DNS translation table is used.
    Note 2: The HTTP request header field "Host" is not updated, so it might happen that you call the Web server with the wrong host name.
    dfischer.utils.DynamicProtobufContentParser(String, String, boolean, byte[])
